d\vec{B} = \frac{\mu_0}{4\pi} \frac{I(d\vec{l} \times \hat{r})}{r^2}

Magnitude: dB = \frac{\mu_0}{4\pi} \frac{I \, dl \sin\theta}{r^2}

\mu_0 = 4\pi \times 10^{-7} \text{ T}\cdot\text{m/A}

B = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2\pi r}

Derived by integrating Biot-Savart from -\infty to +\infty.
Field lines are concentric circles; direction by right-hand rule.

B = \frac{\mu_0 N I}{2R}

Field is perpendicular to loop plane.
Direction: curl fingers along current, thumb gives \vec{B}.

B = \frac{\mu_0 N I R^2}{2(x^2 + R^2)^{3/2}}

At center (x = 0): B = \frac{\mu_0 N I}{2R}

For x \gg R: B \approx \frac{\mu_0 N I R^2}{2x^3} (dipole-like falloff)

B = \frac{\mu_0 I \theta}{4\pi R}

where \theta is in radians.

Full circle (\theta = 2\pi): B = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2R}
Semicircle (\theta = \pi): B = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4R}

B = \mu_0 n I = \frac{\mu_0 N I}{l}

n = \frac{N}{l} = turns per unit length

**Inside**: uniform, independent of position or radius
**Outside**: approximately zero
**At end**: B_{\text{end}} = \frac{\mu_0 n I}{2}

\oint \vec{B} \cdot d\vec{l} = \mu_0 I_{\text{enc}}

Line integral of B around any closed Amperian loop equals \mu_0 times the net current threading through the loop.

Useful when current distribution has high symmetry.

r = \frac{mv}{qB} \quad T = \frac{2\pi m}{qB} \quad f = \frac{qB}{2\pi m}

Derived from: qvB = \frac{mv^2}{r}

**T and f are independent of v and r** (cyclotron principle).

At equilibrium: NIAB = C\phi

\phi = \frac{NIAB}{C}

**Current sensitivity**: \frac{\phi}{I} = \frac{NAB}{C}

**Voltage sensitivity**: \frac{\phi}{V} = \frac{NAB}{CR}

C = torsional spring constant, R = coil resistance.

**Answer: B**

