r = \frac{mv}{qB}

r_p = \frac{m_p v}{eB}, \quad r_\alpha = \frac{4m_p v}{2eB} = \frac{2m_p v}{eB}

r_p : r_\alpha = 1 : 2

The alpha particle traces a larger circle because its mass-to-charge ratio (m/q = 2m_p/e) is double that of the proton (m/q = m_p/e).

**Answer: B**

Each side subtends 60 deg at center. Perpendicular distance from center to each side: d = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}a

Field due to one side (finite wire): B_1 = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi d}(\sin 30° + \sin 30°) = \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}a} \times 1 = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2\sqrt{3}\pi a}

Total for 6 sides (all fields point same direction): B = 6 \times \frac{\mu_0 I}{2\sqrt{3}\pi a} = \frac{3\mu_0 I}{\sqrt{3}\pi a} = \frac{\sqrt{3}\mu_0 I}{\pi a}

**Answer: B (45 deg)**

Pitch: P = v\cos\theta \times \frac{2\pi m}{qB}

Circumference: C = 2\pi r = 2\pi \times \frac{mv\sin\theta}{qB} = \frac{2\pi m v\sin\theta}{qB}

Setting P = C:
v\cos\theta \times \frac{2\pi m}{qB} = \frac{2\pi m v\sin\theta}{qB}

\cos\theta = \sin\theta \implies \theta = 45°

